[src:intent-based-networking/autonomic-computing] The AC system concept is designed to make adaptive decisions, using high-level policies.
[src:intent-based-networking/autonomic-computing] It will constantly check and optimize its status and automatically adapt itself to changing conditions.
[src:intent-based-networking/autonomic-computing] An autonomic computing framework is composed of autonomic components (AC) interacting with each other.
[src:intent-based-networking/autonomic-computing] An AC can be modeled in terms of two main control schemes (local and global) with sensors (for self-monitoring), effectors (for self-adjustment), knowledge and planner/adapter for exploiting policies based on self- and environment awareness.
[src:intent-based-networking/autonomic-computing] This architecture is sometimes referred to as Monitor-Analyze-Plan-Execute (MAPE).
[src:intent-based-networking/autonomic-computing] Driven by such vision, a variety of architectural frameworks based on "self-regulating" autonomic components has been recently proposed.
[src:intent-based-networking/autonomic-computing] A similar trend has recently characterized significant research in the area of multi-agent systems.
[src:intent-based-networking/autonomic-computing] However, most of these approaches are typically conceived with centralized or cluster-based server architectures in mind and mostly address the need of reducing management costs rather than the need of enabling complex software systems or providing innovative services.
[src:intent-based-networking/autonomic-computing] Some autonomic systems involve mobile agents interacting via loosely coupled communication mechanisms.
[src:intent-based-networking/autonomic-computing] Forecasts suggested that the computing devices in use would grow at 38% per year and the average complexity of each device was increasing.
[src:intent-based-networking/autonomic-computing] This volume and complexity was managed by highly skilled humans; but the demand for skilled IT personnel was already outstripping supply, with labour costs exceeding equipment costs by a ratio of up to 18:1.
[src:intent-based-networking/autonomic-computing] Computing systems have brought great benefits of speed and automation but there is now an overwhelming economic need to automate their maintenance.
[src:intent-based-networking/autonomic-computing] In a 2003 IEEE *Computer* article, Kephart and Chess warn that the dream of interconnectivity of computing systems and devices could become the "nightmare of pervasive computing" in which architects are unable to anticipate, design and maintain the complexity of interactions.
[src:intent-based-networking/autonomic-computing] They state the essence of autonomic computing is system self-management, freeing administrators from low-level task management while delivering better system behavior.
[src:intent-based-networking/autonomic-computing] A general problem of modern distributed computing systems is that their complexity, and in particular the complexity of their management, is becoming a significant limiting factor in their further development.
[src:intent-based-networking/autonomic-computing] Large companies and institutions are employing large-scale computer networks for communication and computation.
[src:intent-based-networking/autonomic-computing] The distributed applications running on these computer networks are diverse and deal with multiple tasks, ranging from internal control processes to presenting web content to customer support.
[src:intent-based-networking/autonomic-computing] Additionally, mobile computing is pervading these networks at an increasing speed: employees need to communicate with their companies while they are not in their office.
[src:intent-based-networking/autonomic-computing] They do so by using laptops, personal digital assistants, or mobile phones with diverse forms of wireless technologies to access their companies' data.
[src:intent-based-networking/autonomic-computing] This creates an enormous complexity in the overall computer network which is hard to control manually by human operators.
[src:intent-based-networking/autonomic-computing] Manual control is time-consuming, expensive, and error-prone.
[src:intent-based-networking/autonomic-computing] The manual effort needed to control a growing networked computer-system tends to increase quickly.
[src:intent-based-networking/autonomic-computing] 80% of such problems in infrastructure happen at the client specific application and database layer.
[src:intent-based-networking/autonomic-computing] Most 'autonomic' service providers guarantee only up to the basic plumbing layer (power, hardware, operating system, network and basic database parameters).
[src:intent-based-networking/autonomic-computing] A possible solution could be to enable modern, networked computing systems to manage themselves without direct human intervention.
[src:intent-based-networking/autonomic-computing] The *Autonomic Computing Initiative* (ACI) aims at providing the foundation for autonomic systems.
[src:intent-based-networking/autonomic-computing] It is inspired by the autonomic nervous system of the human body.
[src:intent-based-networking/autonomic-computing] This nervous system controls important bodily functions (e.g. respiration, heart rate, and blood pressure) without any conscious intervention.
[src:intent-based-networking/autonomic-computing] In a self-managing autonomic system, the human operator takes on a new role: instead of controlling the system directly, he/she defines general policies and rules that guide the self-management process.
[src:intent-based-networking/autonomic-computing] For this process, IBM defined the following four types of property referred to as self-star (also called self-*, self-x, or auto-*) properties.
[src:intent-based-networking/autonomic-computing] Self-protection: Proactive identification and protection from arbitrary attacks.
[src:intent-based-networking/autonomic-computing] Self-awareness (also called Self-inspection and Self-decision): System must know itself.
[src:intent-based-networking/autonomic-computing] It must know the extent of its own resources and the resources it links to.
[src:intent-based-networking/autonomic-computing] Self-creation (also called Self-assembly, Self-replication): System driven by ecological and social type models without explicit pressure or involvement from outside the system.
[src:intent-based-networking/autonomic-computing] Self-management (also called self-governance): A system that manages itself without external intervention.
[src:intent-based-networking/autonomic-computing] What is being managed can vary dependent on the system and application.
[src:intent-based-networking/autonomic-computing] Self-description (also called self-explanation or Self-representation): A system explains itself.
[src:intent-based-networking/autonomic-computing] It is capable of being understood (by humans) without further explanation.
[src:intent-based-networking/autonomic-computing] 8. anticipate the demand on its resources while staying transparent to users.
[src:intent-based-networking/autonomic-computing] Adaptive: An autonomic system must be able to change its operation (i.e., its configuration, state and functions).
[src:intent-based-networking/autonomic-computing] This will allow the system to cope with temporal and spatial changes in its operational context either long term (environment customisation/optimisation) or short term (exceptional conditions such as malicious attacks, faults, etc.).
[src:intent-based-networking/autonomic-computing] Aware: An autonomic system must be able to monitor (sense) its operational context as well as its internal state in order to be able to assess if its current operation serves its purpose.
[src:intent-based-networking/autonomic-computing] Awareness will control adaptation of its operational behaviour in response to context or state changes.
[src:intent-based-networking/autonomic-computing] The design complexity of Autonomic Systems can be simplified by utilizing design patterns such as the model–view–controller (MVC) pattern to improve concern separation by encapsulating functional concerns.
[src:intent-based-networking/autonomic-computing] A basic concept that will be applied in Autonomic Systems are closed control loops.
[src:intent-based-networking/autonomic-computing] This well-known concept stems from Process Control Theory.
[src:intent-based-networking/autonomic-computing] Essentially, a closed control loop in a self-managing system monitors some resource (software or hardware component) and autonomously tries to keep its parameters within a desired range.
[src:intent-based-networking/autonomic-computing] According to IBM, hundreds or even thousands of these control loops are expected to work in a large-scale self-managing computer system.
[src:intent-based-networking/autonomic-computing] A fundamental building block of an autonomic system is the sensing capability (*Sensors Si*), which enables the system to observe its external operational context.
[src:intent-based-networking/autonomic-computing] Inherent to an autonomic system is the knowledge of the *Purpose* (intention) and the *Know-how* to operate itself (e.g., bootstrapping, configuration knowledge, interpretation of sensory data, etc.) without external intervention.
[src:intent-based-networking/autonomic-computing] The actual operation of the autonomic system is dictated by the *Logic*, which is responsible for making the right decisions to serve its *Purpose*, and influence by the observation of the operational context (based on the sensor input).
[src:intent-based-networking/autonomic-computing] This model highlights the fact that the operation of an autonomic system is purpose-driven.
[src:intent-based-networking/autonomic-computing] This includes its mission (e.g., the service it is supposed to offer), the policies (e.g., that define the basic behaviour), and the "survival instinct".
[src:intent-based-networking/autonomic-computing] If seen as a control system this would be encoded as a feedback error function or in a heuristically assisted system as an algorithm combined with set of heuristics bounding its operational space.
[src:intent-based-networking/autonomic-networking] The ever-growing management complexity of the Internet caused by its rapid growth is seen by some experts as a major problem that limits its usability in the future.
[src:intent-based-networking/autonomic-networking] What's more, increasingly popular smartphones, PDAs, networked audio and video equipment, and game consoles need to be interconnected.
[src:intent-based-networking/autonomic-networking] Pervasive Computing not only adds features, but also burdens existing networking infrastructure with more and more tasks that sooner or later will not be manageable by human intervention alone.
[src:intent-based-networking/autonomic-networking] Another important aspect is the price of manually controlling huge numbers of vitally important devices of current network infrastructures.
[src:intent-based-networking/autonomic-networking] The autonomic nervous system (ANS) is the part of complex biological nervous systems that is not consciously controlled.
[src:intent-based-networking/autonomic-networking] It regulates bodily functions and the activity of specific organs.
[src:intent-based-networking/autonomic-networking] As proposed by IBM, future communication systems might be designed in a similar way to the ANS.
[src:intent-based-networking/autonomic-networking] As autonomics conceptually derives from biological entities such as the human autonomic nervous system, each of the areas can be metaphorically related to functional and structural aspects of a living being.
[src:intent-based-networking/autonomic-networking] In the human body, the autonomic system facilitates and regulates a variety of functions including respiration, blood pressure and circulation, and emotive response.
[src:intent-based-networking/autonomic-networking] The autonomic nervous system is the interconnecting fabric that supports feedback loops between internal states and various sources by which internal and external conditions are monitored.
[src:intent-based-networking/autonomic-networking] Autognostics includes a range of self-discovery, awareness, and analysis capabilities that provide the autonomic system with a view on high-level state.
[src:intent-based-networking/autonomic-networking] In metaphor, this represents the perceptual sub-systems that gather, analyze, and report on internal and external states and conditions – for example, this might be viewed as the eyes, visual cortex and perceptual organs of the system.
[src:intent-based-networking/autonomic-networking] Autognostics, or literally "self-knowledge", provides the autonomic system with a basis for response and validation.
[src:intent-based-networking/autonomic-networking] A rich autognostic capability may include many different "perceptual senses".
[src:intent-based-networking/autonomic-networking] For example, the human body gathers information via the usual five senses, the so-called sixth sense of proprioception (sense of body position and orientation), and through emotive states that represent the gross wellness of the body.
[src:intent-based-networking/autonomic-networking] As conditions and states change, they are detected by the sensory monitors and provide the basis for adaptation of related systems.
[src:intent-based-networking/autonomic-networking] Most of these sources represent relatively raw and unprocessed views that have limited relevance.
[src:intent-based-networking/autonomic-networking] Post-processing and various forms of analysis must be applied to generate meaningful measurements and assessments against which current state can be derived.
[src:intent-based-networking/autonomic-networking] Configuration management is responsible for the interaction with network elements and interfaces.
[src:intent-based-networking/autonomic-networking] It includes an accounting capability with historical perspective that provides for the tracking of configurations over time, with respect to various circumstances.
[src:intent-based-networking/autonomic-networking] In the biological metaphor, these are the hands and, to some degree, the memory of the autonomic system.
[src:intent-based-networking/autonomic-networking] On a network, remediation and provisioning are applied via configuration setting of specific devices.
[src:intent-based-networking/autonomic-networking] Implementation affecting access and selective performance with respect to role and relationship are also applied.
[src:intent-based-networking/autonomic-networking] Almost all the "actions" that are currently taken by human engineers fall under this area.
[src:intent-based-networking/autonomic-networking] With only a few exceptions, interfaces are set by hand, or by extension of the hand, through automated scripts.
[src:intent-based-networking/autonomic-networking] Implicit in the configuration process is the maintenance of a dynamic population of devices under management, a historical record of changes and the directives which invoked change.
[src:intent-based-networking/autonomic-networking] Typical to many accounting functions, configuration management should be capable of operating on devices and then rolling back changes to recover previous configurations.
[src:intent-based-networking/autonomic-networking] Where change may lead to unrecoverable states, the sub-system should be able to qualify the consequences of changes prior to issuing them.
[src:intent-based-networking/autonomic-networking] As directives for change must originate from other sub-systems, the shared language for such directives must be abstracted from the details of the devices involved.
[src:intent-based-networking/autonomic-networking] The configuration management sub-system must be able to translate unambiguously between directives and hard actions or to be able to signal the need for further detail on a directive.
[src:intent-based-networking/autonomic-networking] An inferential capacity may be appropriate to support sufficient flexibility (i.e. configuration never takes place because there is no unique one-to-one mapping between directive and configuration settings).
[src:intent-based-networking/autonomic-networking] Where standards are not sufficient, a learning capacity may also be required to acquire new knowledge of devices and their configuration.
[src:intent-based-networking/autonomic-networking] Policy management includes policy specification, deployment, reasoning over policies, updating and maintaining policies, and enforcement.
[src:intent-based-networking/autonomic-networking] It provides the models of environment and behavior that represent effective interaction according to specific goals.
[src:intent-based-networking/autonomic-networking] In the human nervous system metaphor, these models are implicit in the evolutionary "design" of biological entities and specific to the goals of survival and procreation.
[src:intent-based-networking/autonomic-networking] Definition of what constitutes a policy is necessary to consider what is involved in managing it.
[src:intent-based-networking/autonomic-networking] A relatively flexible and abstract framework of values, relationships, roles, interactions, resources, and other components of the network environment is required.
[src:intent-based-networking/autonomic-networking] This sub-system extends far beyond the physical network to the applications in use and the processes and end-users that employ the network to achieve specific goals.
[src:intent-based-networking/autonomic-networking] It must express the relative values of various resources, outcomes, and processes and include a basis for assessing states and conditions.
[src:intent-based-networking/autonomic-networking] Unless embodied in some system outside the autonomic network or implicit to the specific policy implementation, the framework must also accommodate the definition of process, objectives and goals.
[src:intent-based-networking/autonomic-networking] Business process definitions and descriptions are then an integral part of the policy implementation.
[src:intent-based-networking/autonomic-networking] Further, as policy management represents the ultimate basis for the operation of the autonomic system, it must be able to report on its operation with respect to the details of its implementation.
[src:intent-based-networking/autonomic-networking] Autodefense represents a dynamic and adaptive mechanism that responds to malicious and intentional attacks on the network infrastructure, or use of the network infrastructure to attack IT resources.
[src:intent-based-networking/autonomic-networking] As defensive measures tend to impede the operation of IT, it is optimally capable of balancing performance objectives with typically over-riding threat management actions.
[src:intent-based-networking/autonomic-networking] In the biological metaphor, this sub-system offers mechanisms comparable to the immune system.
[src:intent-based-networking/autonomic-networking] This sub-system must proactively assess network and application infrastructure for risks, detect and identify threats, and define effective both proactive and reactive defensive responses.
[src:intent-based-networking/autonomic-networking] It has the role of the warrior and the security guard insofar as it has roles for both maintenance and corrective activities.
[src:intent-based-networking/autonomic-networking] Its relationship with security is close but not identical – security is more concerned with appropriately defined and implemented access and authorization controls to maintain legitimate roles and process.
[src:intent-based-networking/autonomic-networking] Autodefense deals with forces and processes, typically malicious, outside the normal operation of the system that offer some risk to successful execution.
[src:intent-based-networking/autonomic-networking] Autodefense requires high-level and detailed knowledge of the entire network as well as imbedded models of risk that allow it to analyze dynamically the current status.
[src:intent-based-networking/autonomic-networking] Corrections to decrease risk must be considered in balance with performance objectives and value of process goals – an overzealous defensive response can immobilize the system (like the immune system inappropriately invoking an allergic reaction).
[src:intent-based-networking/autonomic-networking] The detection of network or application behaviors that signal possible attack or abuse is followed by the generation of an appropriate response – for example, ports might be temporarily closed or packets with a specific source or destination might be filtered out.
[src:intent-based-networking/autonomic-networking] Further assessment generates subsequent changes either relaxing the defensive measures or strengthening them.
[src:intent-based-networking/autonomic-networking] It also may receive definition of relative value of various resources and processes from policy management in order to develop responses consistent with policy.
[src:intent-based-networking/autonomic-networking] Security provides the structure that defines and enforces the relationships between roles, content, and resources, particularly with respect to access.
[src:intent-based-networking/autonomic-networking] It includes the framework for definitions as well as the means to implement them.
[src:intent-based-networking/autonomic-networking] In metaphor, security parallels the complex mechanisms underlying social interactions, defining friends, foes, mates and allies and offering access to limited resources on the basis of assessed benefit.
[src:intent-based-networking/autonomic-networking] Several key means are employed by security – they include the well-known 3 As of authentication, authorization, and access (control).
[src:intent-based-networking/autonomic-networking] The basis for applying these means requires the definition of roles and their relationships to resources, processes and each other.
[src:intent-based-networking/autonomic-networking] High-level concepts like privacy, anonymity and verification are likely imbedded in the form of the role definitions and derive from policy.
[src:intent-based-networking/autonomic-networking] Successful security reliably supports and enforces roles and relationships.
[src:intent-based-networking/autonomic-networking] Autodefense has a close association with security – maintaining the assigned roles in balance with performance exposes the system to potential violations in security.
[src:intent-based-networking/autonomic-networking] In those cases, the system must compensate by making changes that may sacrifice balance on a temporary basis and indeed may violate the operational terms of security itself.
[src:intent-based-networking/autonomic-networking] Typically the two are viewed as inextricably intertwined – effective security somewhat hopefully negating any need for a defensive response.
[src:intent-based-networking/autonomic-networking] Security's revised role is to mediate between the competing demands from policy for maximized performance and minimized risk with auto defense recovering the balance when inevitable risk translates to threat.
[src:intent-based-networking/autonomic-networking] Federation represents one of the key challenges to be solved by effective security.
[src:intent-based-networking/autonomic-networking] The connection fabric supports the interaction with all the elements and sub-systems of the autonomic system.
[src:intent-based-networking/autonomic-networking] It may be composed of a variety of means and mechanisms, or may be a single central framework.
[src:intent-based-networking/autonomic-networking] The biological equivalent is the central nervous system itself – although referred to as the autonomic system, it actually is only the communication conduit between the human body's faculties.
[src:intent-based-networking/autonomic-networking] Consequently, it is currently under research by many research projects, how principles and paradigms of mother nature might be applied to networking.
[src:intent-based-networking/autonomic-networking] Instead of a layering approach, autonomic networking targets a more flexible structure termed compartmentalization.
[src:intent-based-networking/autonomic-networking] Functions should be divided into atomic units to allow for maximal re-composition freedom.
[src:intent-based-networking/autonomic-networking] A fundamental concept of Control theory, the closed control loop, is among the fundamental principles of autonomic networking.
[src:intent-based-networking/autonomic-networking] A closed control loop maintains the properties of the controlled system within desired bounds by constantly monitoring target parameters.
[src:intent-based-networking/intent-based-networking] Rather than relying on low-level commands to configure the network, administrators define these high-level intents, and the network dynamically adjusts itself to meet these requirements.
[src:intent-based-networking/intent-based-networking] IBN simplifies the management of complex networks by ensuring that the network infrastructure aligns with the desired operational goals.
[src:intent-based-networking/intent-based-networking] For example, an implementer can explicitly state a network purpose with a policy such as "Allow hosts A and B to communicate with X bandwidth capacity" without the need to understand the detailed mechanisms of the underlying devices (e.g. switches), topology or routing configurations.
[src:intent-based-networking/intent-based-networking] Advances in Natural Language Understanding (NLU) systems, along with neural network-based algorithms like BERT, RoBERTa, GLUE, and ERNIE, have enabled the conversion of user queries into structured representations that can be processed by automated services.
[src:intent-based-networking/intent-based-networking] This capability is crucial for managing the increasing complexity of network services.
[src:intent-based-networking/intent-based-networking] Intent-Based Networking (IBN) leverages these advancements to simplify network management by abstracting network services, reducing operational complexity, and lowering costs.
[src:intent-based-networking/intent-based-networking] A proposed three-layered architecture integrates intent-based automation into network management systems.
[src:intent-based-networking/intent-based-networking] In the **business layer**, intents are based on Key Performance Indicators (KPIs) and Service Level Agreements (SLAs), reflecting business objectives.
[src:intent-based-networking/intent-based-networking] The **intent layer** evaluates and re-plans actions dynamically, where a **Knowledge** module abstracts and reasons about intents, while an **Agent** interfaces with network objects to execute actions.
[src:intent-based-networking/intent-based-networking] The **data layer** observes network objects, updates topology information, and interacts with the Knowledge and Agent modules to ensure accurate and timely responses to network changes.
[src:intent-based-networking/intent-based-networking] At the bottom, the **network layer** contains the physical infrastructure, transforming network data into a usable format for the intent layer to act upon.
[src:intent-based-networking/network-automation] In July 2004, Dustin Snell launched Network Automation, Inc. in Los Angeles, California.
[src:intent-based-networking/network-automation] In September 2012, after two years as Chief Software Architect, Snell resumed his role as CEO.
[src:intent-based-networking/network-automation] In April 2014, the company was acquired by Minneapolis, Minnesota–based HelpSystems, an IT software company offering solutions in the areas of systems and network management, business intelligence, security and compliance, for IBM i, Unix, Linux and Windows environments.
[src:intent-based-networking/network-automation] The company’s main products were AutoMate and AutoMate BPA Server, which ran on Windows operating systems.
[src:intent-based-networking/network-automation] The products were designed to simplify repetitive IT tasks via a drag and drop GUI interface, without requiring end user coding.
[src:intent-based-networking/network-automation] Functions included job scheduling, automated FTP, batch processing, automated backups, scripting, automated testing, event log monitoring and automated reporting.
[src:intent-based-networking/network-automation] 2012 enhancements included support for Windows Azure and Amazon Web Services.
[src:intent-based-networking/network-automation] Third party applications such as Microsoft CRM could also be integrated.
[src:intent-based-networking/network-automation] Advanced Systems Concepts, Inc. was a California court case decided in favor of Network Automation on March 8, 2011.
[src:intent-based-networking/network-automation] The Ninth Circuit Court verdict protected the rights of companies to use strategic keywords in Internet search advertising.
[src:intent-based-networking/network-automation] AutoMate won awards from Windows IT Pro, CNET and NetworkWorld and was named as the "Best Scripting Tool" by *Redmondmag*.
[src:intent-based-networking/network-automation] The company was named to the 2009, 2011 and 2012 Inc.
[src:intent-based-networking/network-automation] 5000 as one of the fastest growing software companies in the US.
[src:intent-based-networking/network-management] A number of applications and protocols exist to support network and network device management.
[src:intent-based-networking/network-management] Network management allows IT professionals to monitor network components within a large network area.
[src:intent-based-networking/network-management] Access methods include the SNMP, command-line interface (CLI), custom XML, CMIP, Windows Management Instrumentation (WMI), Transaction Language 1 (TL1), CORBA, NETCONF, RESTCONF and the Java Management Extensions (JMX).
[src:intent-based-networking/network-management] Schemas include the Structure of Management Information (SMI), YANG, WBEM, the Common Information Model (CIM Schema), and MTOSI amongst others.
[src:intent-based-networking/network-management] Effective network management can provide positive strategic impacts.
[src:intent-based-networking/network-management] For example, in the case of developing an infrastructure, providing participants with some interactive space allows them to collaborate with each other, thereby promoting overall benefits.
[src:intent-based-networking/network-management] At the same time, the value of network management to the strategic network is also affected by the relationship between participants.
[src:intent-based-networking/network-management] Active participation, interaction and collaboration can make them more trusting of each other and enhance cohesion.
[src:intent-based-networking/software-defined-networking] SDN was commonly associated with the OpenFlow protocol for remote communication with network plane elements to determine the path of network packets across network switches since OpenFlow's emergence in 2011.
[src:intent-based-networking/software-defined-networking] However, since 2012, proprietary systems have also used the term.
[src:intent-based-networking/software-defined-networking] These include Cisco Systems' Open Network Environment and Nicira's network virtualization platform.
[src:intent-based-networking/software-defined-networking] SD-WAN applies similar technology to a wide area network (WAN).
[src:intent-based-networking/software-defined-networking] In addition to WAN use cases, SDN is also increasingly applied in telecom backbones, where it is paired with operational inventory and automation platforms to provide real-time visibility, service assurance, and simplified provisioning across multi-vendor networks.
[src:intent-based-networking/software-defined-networking] The history of SDN principles can be traced back to the separation of the control and data planes first used in public switched telephone networks.
[src:intent-based-networking/software-defined-networking] This provided a manner of simplifying provisioning and management years before the architecture was used in data networks.
[src:intent-based-networking/software-defined-networking] The Internet Engineering Task Force (IETF) began considering various ways to decouple the control and data forwarding functions in a proposed interface standard published in 2004 named Forwarding and Control Element Separation (ForCES).
[src:intent-based-networking/software-defined-networking] The ForCES Working Group also proposed a companion SoftRouter architecture.
[src:intent-based-networking/software-defined-networking] Additional early standards from the IETF that pursued separating control from data planes include the Linux Netlink as an IP services protocol, and a path computation element (PCE)-based architecture.
[src:intent-based-networking/software-defined-networking] These early attempts failed to gain traction.
[src:intent-based-networking/software-defined-networking] One reason is that many in the Internet community viewed separating control from data to be risky, especially given the potential for failure in the control plane.
[src:intent-based-networking/software-defined-networking] Another reason is that vendors were concerned that creating standard application programming interfaces (APIs) between the control and data planes would result in increased competition.
[src:intent-based-networking/software-defined-networking] In 2006 a young startup was founded around SDN style network topology and submitted a collection of SDN patents in 2007.
[src:intent-based-networking/software-defined-networking] The use of open-source software in these separated architectures traces its roots to the Ethane project at Stanford's computer science department.
[src:intent-based-networking/software-defined-networking] Ethane's simple switch design led to the creation of OpenFlow, and an API for OpenFlow was first created in 2008.
[src:intent-based-networking/software-defined-networking] In that same year, NOX, an operating system for networks, was created.
[src:intent-based-networking/software-defined-networking] SDN research included emulators such as vSDNEmul, EstiNet, and Mininet.
[src:intent-based-networking/software-defined-networking] Work on OpenFlow continued at Stanford, including with the creation of testbeds to evaluate the use of the protocol in a single campus network, as well as across the WAN as a backbone for connecting multiple campuses.
[src:intent-based-networking/software-defined-networking] In academic settings, there were several research and production networks based on OpenFlow switches from NEC and Hewlett-Packard, as well as those based on Quanta Computer white-boxes starting in about 2009.
[src:intent-based-networking/software-defined-networking] Beyond academia, the first deployments were by Nicira in 2010 to control OVS from Onix, codeveloped with NTT and Google.
[src:intent-based-networking/software-defined-networking] A notable deployment was Google's B4 in 2012.
[src:intent-based-networking/software-defined-networking] Later, Google announced the first OpenFlow/Onix deployments in is datacenters.
[src:intent-based-networking/software-defined-networking] Another large deployment exists at China Mobile.
[src:intent-based-networking/software-defined-networking] The Open Networking Foundation was founded in 2011 to promote SDN and OpenFlow.
