[src:intent-based-networking/software-defined-networking] An SDN Application consists of SDN application logic and one or more NBI drivers.
[src:intent-based-networking/software-defined-networking] SDN applications may themselves expose another layer of abstracted network control, thus offering one or more higher-level NBIs through respective NBI agents.
[src:intent-based-networking/software-defined-networking] The SDN controller is a logically centralized entity in charge of (i) translating the requirements from the SDN application layer down to the SDN datapaths and (ii) providing the SDN applications with an abstract view of the network (which may include statistics and events).
[src:intent-based-networking/software-defined-networking] An SDN controller consists of one or more NBI agents, the SDN control logic, and the control to data-plane interface (CDPI) driver.
[src:intent-based-networking/software-defined-networking] The SDN datapath is a logical network device that exposes visibility and uncontested control over its advertised forwarding and data processing capabilities.
[src:intent-based-networking/software-defined-networking] The logical representation may encompass all or a subset of the capabilities.
[src:intent-based-networking/software-defined-networking] An SDN datapath consists of a CDPI agent and a set of one or more traffic forwarding engines and zero or more traffic processing functions.
[src:intent-based-networking/software-defined-networking] These engines and functions may include simple forwarding between the datapath's external interfaces or internal traffic processing or termination functions.
[src:intent-based-networking/software-defined-networking] One or more SDN datapaths may be contained in a single (physical) network element—an integrated physical combination of communications resources, managed as a unit.
[src:intent-based-networking/software-defined-networking] An SDN datapath may also be defined across multiple physical network elements.
[src:intent-based-networking/software-defined-networking] The SDN CDPI is the interface defined between an SDN controller and an SDN datapath, which provides at least programmatic control of all forwarding operations, capabilities advertisement, statistics reporting, and event notification.
[src:intent-based-networking/software-defined-networking] One value of SDN lies in the expectation that the CDPI is implemented in an open, vendor-neutral and interoperable way.
[src:intent-based-networking/software-defined-networking] SDN NBIs are interfaces between SDN applications and SDN controllers and typically provide abstract network views and enable direct expression of network behavior and requirements.
[src:intent-based-networking/software-defined-networking] This may occur at any level of abstraction and across different sets of functionality.
[src:intent-based-networking/software-defined-networking] The implementation of the SDN control plane can follow a centralized, hierarchical, or decentralized design.
[src:intent-based-networking/software-defined-networking] Initial SDN control plane proposals focused on a centralized solution, where a single control entity had a global view of the network.
[src:intent-based-networking/software-defined-networking] While this simplifies the implementation of the control logic, it has scalability limitations as the size and dynamics of the network increase.
[src:intent-based-networking/software-defined-networking] To overcome these limitations, hierarchical and distributed approaches have been proposed.
[src:intent-based-networking/software-defined-networking] In hierarchical solutions, controllers operate on a partitioned network view, while decisions that require network-wide knowledge are taken by a logically centralized root controller.
[src:intent-based-networking/software-defined-networking] In distributed approaches, controllers operate on their local view or they may exchange synchronization messages to enhance their knowledge.
[src:intent-based-networking/software-defined-networking] Distributed solutions are more suitable for supporting adaptive SDN applications.
[src:intent-based-networking/software-defined-networking] A key issue when designing a distributed SDN control plane is to decide on the number and placement of control entities.
[src:intent-based-networking/software-defined-networking] An important parameter to consider while doing so is the propagation delay between the controllers and the network devices, especially in the context of large networks.
[src:intent-based-networking/software-defined-networking] Other objectives that have been considered involve control path reliability, fault tolerance, and application requirements.
[src:intent-based-networking/software-defined-networking] In SDN, the data plane is responsible for processing data-carrying packets using a set of rules specified by the control plane.
[src:intent-based-networking/software-defined-networking] The data plane may be implemented in physical hardware switches or in software, such as Open vSwitch.
[src:intent-based-networking/software-defined-networking] The memory capacity of hardware switches may limit the number of rules that can be stored whereas software implementations may have higher capacity.
[src:intent-based-networking/software-defined-networking] Flow table entries may be populated in a proactive, reactive, or hybrid fashion.
[src:intent-based-networking/software-defined-networking] In the proactive mode, the controller populates flow table entries for all possible traffic matches for this switch in advance.
[src:intent-based-networking/software-defined-networking] This mode can be compared with typical routing table entries today, where all static entries are installed ahead of time.
[src:intent-based-networking/software-defined-networking] Following this, no request is sent to the controller since all incoming flows will find a matching entry.
[src:intent-based-networking/software-defined-networking] A major advantage in proactive mode is that all packets are forwarded at line rate (considering all flow table entries in TCAM) and no delay is added.
[src:intent-based-networking/software-defined-networking] In the reactive mode, entries are populated on demand.
[src:intent-based-networking/software-defined-networking] If a packet arrives without a corresponding match rule in the flow table, the SDN agent sends a request to the controller for further instruction.
[src:intent-based-networking/software-defined-networking] The controller examines the SDN agent requests and provides instructions, installing a rule in the flow table for the corresponding packet if necessary.
[src:intent-based-networking/software-defined-networking] The hybrid mode uses the low-latency proactive forwarding mode for a portion of traffic while relying on the flexibility of reactive mode processing for the remaining traffic.
[src:intent-based-networking/software-defined-networking] Software-defined mobile networking (SDMN) is an approach to the design of mobile networks where all protocol-specific features are implemented in software, maximizing the use of generic and commodity hardware and software in both the core network and radio access network.
[src:intent-based-networking/software-defined-networking] It is proposed as an extension of SDN paradigm to incorporate mobile network specific functionalities.
[src:intent-based-networking/software-defined-networking] Since 3GPP Rel.14, a Control User Plane Separation was introduced in the Mobile Core Network architectures with the PFCP protocol.
[src:intent-based-networking/software-defined-networking] An SD-WAN is a WAN managed using the principles of software-defined networking.
[src:intent-based-networking/software-defined-networking] The main driver of SD-WAN is to lower WAN costs using more affordable and commercially available leased lines, as an alternative or partial replacement of more expensive MPLS lines.
[src:intent-based-networking/software-defined-networking] Control and management are administered separately from the hardware, with central controllers allowing for easier configuration and administration.
[src:intent-based-networking/software-defined-networking] An SD-LAN is a Local area network (LAN) built around the principles of software-defined networking, though there are key differences in topology, network security, application visibility and control, management and quality of service.
[src:intent-based-networking/software-defined-networking] SD-LAN decouples control, management and data planes to enable a policy-driven architecture for wired and wireless LANs.
[src:intent-based-networking/software-defined-networking] SD-LANs are characterized by their use of a cloud management system and wireless connectivity without the presence of a physical controller.
[src:intent-based-networking/software-defined-networking] SDN architecture may enable, facilitate or enhance network-related security applications due to the controller's central view of the network, and its capacity to modify behavior or the data plane at any time.
[src:intent-based-networking/software-defined-networking] The security implications of SDN architecture remain under study.
[src:intent-based-networking/software-defined-networking] Several research works on SDN have already investigated security applications built upon the SDN controller, with different aims in mind.
[src:intent-based-networking/software-defined-networking] Distributed denial of service (DDoS) detection and mitigation, as well as botnet and worm propagation, are some concrete use cases of such applications.
[src:intent-based-networking/software-defined-networking] Proposed applications periodically collect network statistics from the forwarding plane of the network in a standardized manner (e.g., using OpenFlow), and then apply classification algorithms on those statistics in order to detect any network anomalies.
[src:intent-based-networking/software-defined-networking] If an anomaly is detected, the application instructs the controller how to reprogram the data plane in order to mitigate it.
[src:intent-based-networking/software-defined-networking] Another kind of security application leverages the SDN controller by implementing some moving target defense (MTD) algorithms.
[src:intent-based-networking/software-defined-networking] MTD algorithms are typically used to make any attack on a given system or network more difficult than usual by periodically hiding or changing key properties of that system or network.
[src:intent-based-networking/software-defined-networking] In traditional networks, implementing MTD algorithms is not a trivial task since it is difficult to build a central authority able to determine, for each part of the system to be protected, which key properties are hidden or changed.
[src:intent-based-networking/software-defined-networking] In an SDN network, such tasks become more straightforward thanks to the centrality of the controller.
[src:intent-based-networking/software-defined-networking] One application can, for example, periodically assign virtual IPs to hosts within the network, and the mapping of virtual IP to real IP is then performed by the controller.
[src:intent-based-networking/software-defined-networking] Another application can simulate some fake opened/closed/filtered ports on random hosts in the network in order to add significant noise during scanning performed by an attacker.
[src:intent-based-networking/software-defined-networking] Additional value regarding security in SDN-enabled networks can also be gained using FlowVisor and FlowChecker.
[src:intent-based-networking/software-defined-networking] The former tries to use a single hardware forwarding plane sharing multiple separated logical networks.
[src:intent-based-networking/software-defined-networking] Following this approach, the same hardware resources can be used for production and development purposes as well as separating monitoring, configuration and Internet traffic, where each scenario can have its own logical topology, which is called a slice.
[src:intent-based-networking/software-defined-networking] In conjunction with this approach, FlowChecker realizes the validation of new OpenFlow rules that are deployed by users using their own slice.
[src:intent-based-networking/software-defined-networking] SDN controller applications are mostly deployed in large-scale scenarios, which requires comprehensive checks of possible programming errors.
[src:intent-based-networking/software-defined-networking] A system to do this called NICE was described in 2012.
[src:intent-based-networking/software-defined-networking] Introducing an overarching security architecture requires a comprehensive and protracted approach to SDN.
[src:intent-based-networking/software-defined-networking] Since it was introduced, designers are looking at possible ways to secure SDN that do not compromise scalability.
[src:intent-based-networking/software-defined-networking] One architecture called SN-SECA (SDN+NFV) Security Architecture.
[src:intent-based-networking/software-defined-networking] Distributed applications that run across datacenters usually replicate data for the purpose of synchronization, fault resiliency, load balancing and getting data closer to users (which reduces latency to users and increases their perceived throughput).
[src:intent-based-networking/software-defined-networking] Also, many applications, such as Hadoop, replicate data within a datacenter across multiple racks to increase fault tolerance and make data recovery easier.
[src:intent-based-networking/software-defined-networking] All of these operations require data delivery from one machine or datacenter to multiple machines or datacenters.
[src:intent-based-networking/software-defined-networking] The process of reliably delivering data from one machine to multiple machines is referred to as Reliable Group Data Delivery (RGDD).
[src:intent-based-networking/software-defined-networking] SDN switches can be used for RGDD via installation of rules that allow forwarding to multiple outgoing ports.
[src:intent-based-networking/software-defined-networking] For example, OpenFlow provides support for Group Tables since version 1.1 which makes this possible.
[src:intent-based-networking/software-defined-networking] Using SDN, a central controller can carefully and intelligently setup forwarding trees for RGDD.
[src:intent-based-networking/software-defined-networking] Such trees can be built while paying attention to network congestion/load status to improve performance.
[src:intent-based-networking/software-defined-networking] For example, MCTCP is a scheme for delivery to many nodes inside datacenters that relies on regular and structured topologies of datacenter networks while DCCast and QuickCast are approaches for fast and efficient data and content replication across datacenters over private WANs.
[src:intent-based-networking/software-defined-networking] Network Function Virtualization, or NFV for short, is a concept that complements SDN.
[src:intent-based-networking/software-defined-networking] Thus, NFV is not dependent on SDN or SDN concepts.
[src:intent-based-networking/software-defined-networking] NFV separates software from hardware to enable flexible network deployment and dynamic operation.
[src:intent-based-networking/software-defined-networking] NFV deployments typically use commodity servers to run network services software versions that previously were hardware-based.
[src:intent-based-networking/software-defined-networking] These software-based services that run in an NFV environment are called Virtual Network Functions (VNF).
[src:intent-based-networking/software-defined-networking] SDN-NFV hybrid program was provided for high efficiency, elastic and scalable capabilities NFV aimed at accelerating service innovation and provisioning using standard IT virtualization technologies.
[src:intent-based-networking/software-defined-networking] SDN provides the agility of controlling the generic forwarding devices such as the routers and switches by using SDN controllers.
[src:intent-based-networking/software-defined-networking] On the other hand, NFV agility is provided for the network applications by using virtualized servers.
[src:intent-based-networking/software-defined-networking] It is entirely possible to implement a virtualized network function (VNF) as a standalone entity using existing networking and orchestration paradigms.
[src:intent-based-networking/software-defined-networking] However, there are inherent benefits in leveraging SDN concepts to implement and manage an NFV infrastructure, particularly when looking at the management and orchestration of VNFs, and that's why multivendor platforms are being defined that incorporate SDN and NFV in concerted ecosystems.
